meta-zuboard
============

This layer is the ZuBoard implementation of the MNCOS Xilinx ZynqMP demo. It is
intentionally thin so it can act as the template for a future board layer such
as `meta-kr260demo`.

Common FPGA demo mechanics live in `meta-fpga-util`:

- `/usr/bin/fwctl` firmware staging/loading utility
- `apu-rpu-ctl` Linux RPMsg char-device client
- generic PL/RPU firmware packaging class
- ZynqMP JTAG/TFTP export class and loader script

`meta-zuboard` keeps the board-specific pieces:

- ZuBoard firmware asset names, release URLs, checksums and local workspace
  paths in `recipes-bsp/zuboard-firmware/zuboard-firmware_1.0.bb`
- ZuBoard DTS/domain YAML fragments
- U-Boot environment and config for the `zudemo` machine
- production flashing utility and eMMC policy
- product image recipes that install the shared MNCOS package group, ZuBoard
  firmware package, `fwctl`, and `apu-rpu-ctl` for `zudemo`

Dependencies
============

Add the layers in this order:

```sh
bitbake-layers add-layer meta-mncos
bitbake-layers add-layer meta-fpga-util
bitbake-layers add-layer meta-zuboard
```

`meta-zuboard` depends on `meta-fpga-util`, `meta-xilinx-core`, and
`meta-xilinx-standalone`. It also depends on `meta-mncos` for the MNCOS distro,
image identity class, and shared package group.

Template For Another ZynqMP Demo Board
======================================

To create `meta-kr260demo`, copy the shape of this layer but keep shared logic
in `meta-fpga-util`.

Start with these board-specific edits:

1. Rename the layer directory and collection from `meta-zuboard` to
   `meta-kr260demo`.
2. Keep `LAYERDEPENDS_<collection>` pointing at `fpga-util`, `xilinx`, and
   `xilinx-standalone`, plus `mncos`.
3. Create a firmware recipe such as `kr260demo-firmware_1.0.bb` that sets
   `FPGA_FIRMWARE_*` variables and inherits `fpga-firmware-package`.
4. Create product image targets such as `kr260demo-image-minimal` and
   `kr260demo-production-flash-image`; `require
   recipes-core/images/include/mncos-image-common.inc` for the shared MNCOS
   base set, then add `kr260demo-firmware fwctl` (and trim with
   `IMAGE_INSTALL:remove` if needed) in the main image.
5. Replace the machine config, DTS/domain YAML, U-Boot environment, and any
   production flashing policy with KR260 values.

Firmware Control
================

The old `zud` helper is now the shared `fwctl` command from `meta-fpga-util`.
The ZuBoard image installs `/etc/default/fwctl` with:

```sh
FWCTL_FW_SRC="/opt/monutchee/zudemo/firmware"
FWCTL_FW_DST="/lib/firmware"
```

Typical target-side flow:

```sh
fwctl install all
fwctl load all
fwctl start all
```

For compatibility during transition, `fwctl` still honors the old `ZUD_*`
environment variables if the new `FWCTL_*` variables are not set.

Image Targets
=============

Build the main ZuBoard image:

```sh
bitbake zudemo-image
```

Build the ZuBoard production-flash image and the production WIC together:

```sh
bitbake zudemo-production-flash-image
```

The complete bundle is exported to:

```text
build/export/jtag-tftpboot
```

When `load-jtag-image.tcl` starts, it copies the files fetched by U-Boot to
`/srv/tftp` before connecting to the board. The production bundle also copies
`target.wic.xz` and its checksum. The ELF firmware files remain in the export
directory because XSDB downloads them directly over JTAG. To use a different
TFTP root, set `MNCOS_TFTP_ROOT` in the host environment.

Run XSDB from the export bundle directory:

```sh
./load-jtag-image.tcl <hw-server-ip> <tftp-server-ip> [board-ip]
```

With no board IP argument, U-Boot obtains the board address through DHCP. A
static board address is optional:

```sh
./load-jtag-image.tcl 127.0.0.1 192.168.1.10 192.168.1.20
```

After the provisioning Linux boots, write the verified production WIC to the
detected non-removable eMMC device with:

```sh
mncos-flash-emmc
```

If the Linux-side TFTP server differs from the build-time default, pass it to
the flashing utility:

```sh
mncos-flash-emmc --server 192.168.1.10
```
